I am planning some offseason projects and want to experiment with laser cutting Delrin. We have a Trotec Speedy 100 laser. Looking for insights as to settings for cutting 1/4" thick Delrin. The other question is how big to offset holes if we want to press fit bearings into them. I have a small sheet of Delrin and based on the cost would appreciate any settings!

Found this article with some good advice.

Hackaday – 22 Sep 15

Drawbacks Of Laser Cut Delrin–and How To Slip Around Them

Welcome back to part II in this ensemble of techniques with laser-cut Delrin. Thanks for many of the great insights along the way in the comments. In this guide, I’d like to go over some of t…

For press fit bearings, one option would be to go very undersized (like >0.02) and ream it out slowly and see what press fit works. Though if there is a decent axial load, I would use some sort of retainer har or bearing block to hold the bearing as it may elongated and loose the press fit.

Ian_McTavish:

The other question is how big to offset holes if we want to press fit bearings into them.

Once you get the parts cutting, the best way to test fits is with test parts. Here’s one we use to test laser cutter offsets. Cut 2 of them and tweak the dimensions to get a nice fit for the bearing hole, and for the tabs to fit in the slots.

image425×563 4.91 KB

Also, be aware that when you cut material this thick, it’s likely that the cuts will be tapered. So the bearing may fit in the hole better on one side than the other.

What wattage is your machine? Other than general advice like use the air assist, nobody can give you useful parameters without that info.

Trotec has material settings prepopulated in Jobcenter - you may or may not find what you need in there.

Once I know what wattage your machine is I can de-rate our 120W SP500 speeds for your machine and suggest a starting point.
